{
  "texts": [
    "AMR-DA integrates sentence-level techniques like back translation with token-level approaches such as Easy Data Augmentation (EDA) to create a more robust data augmentation framework.",
    "The method is evaluated on two tasks: semantic textual similarity (STS) and text classification.",
    "Results show that AMR-DA enhances state-of-the-art models' performance on multiple STS benchmarks and outperforms existing augmentation techniques like EDA in text classification tasks.",
    "This work is the first to utilize AMR for data augmentation, showing that it can effectively diversify training data and improve model robustness without requiring decoder retraining.",
    "Table 1.1Linguistics aspects that cannot be captured by AMRs.AspectExample Sentence(s)AMRVerb Tense and AspectJohn eats & John is eating(e / eat-01:arg0 (j / John))(e / eat-01Syntactic StructureThe boy ate the apple & The apple was eaten by the boy:arg0 (b / boy):arg1 (a / apple))(s / see-01AmbiguityJohn saw the man with a telescope:arg0 (j / John):arg1 (m / man):manner (t / telescope))(e / eat-01Word OrderOnly John ate the apple & John only ate the apple:arg0 (j / John):arg1 (a / apple))(k / kick-01Figurative LanguageKick the bucket:arg0 (p / person):arg1 (b / bucket))Sentiment and EmotionI am ecstatic & I am happy(h / happy-01:arg0 (i / I))(w / want-01Intentionality vs. Factuality He wants to go:ARG0 (h / he):ARG1 (g / go-02:ARG0 h))(a / absent-01:ARG1 (h / he))Semantic VariationHe was absent & He was not present(p / present-02:polarity -:ARG1 (h / he)) Table 2.2AMRs and Triples for a Gold sentence \"The dog chased the ball\"."
  ]
}